# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aniline
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aniline/1-4-benzoquinone] 1,4-Benzoquinone is prepared industrially by oxidation of hydroquinone, which can be obtained by several routes.
[src:aniline/1-4-benzoquinone] One route involves oxidation of diisopropylbenzene and the Hock rearrangement.
[src:aniline/1-4-benzoquinone] The reaction proceeds via the bis(hydroperoxide) and the hydroquinone.
[src:aniline/1-4-benzoquinone] Both hydroquinone and catechol are produced.
[src:aniline/1-4-benzoquinone] Subsequent oxidation of the hydroquinone gives the quinone.
[src:aniline/1-4-benzoquinone] 1,4-Benzoquinone was originally prepared industrially by oxidation of aniline, for example by manganese dioxide.
[src:aniline/1-4-benzoquinone] This method is mainly practiced in China where environmental regulations are more relaxed.
[src:aniline/1-4-benzoquinone] One such method makes use of hydrogen peroxide as the oxidizer and iodine or an iodine salt as a catalyst for the oxidation occurring in a polar solvent such as isopropyl alcohol.
[src:aniline/1-4-benzoquinone] When heated to near its melting point, 1,4-benzoquinone sublimes, even at atmospheric pressure, allowing for an effective purification.
[src:aniline/1-4-benzoquinone] Impure samples are often dark-colored due to the presence of quinhydrone, a dark green 1:1 charge-transfer complex of quinone with hydroquinone.
[src:aniline/1-4-benzoquinone] Benzoquinone is a planar molecule with localized, alternating C=C, C=O, and C–C bonds.
[src:aniline/1-4-benzoquinone] Reduction gives the semiquinone anion C6H4O2−}, which adopts a more delocalized structure.
[src:aniline/1-4-benzoquinone] Further reduction coupled to protonation gives the hydroquinone, in which the electrons of the C6 ring are fully delocalized.
[src:aniline/1-4-benzoquinone] Benzoquinonium is a skeletal muscle relaxant, ganglion blocking agent that is made from benzoquinone.
[src:aniline/1-4-benzoquinone] It is used as a hydrogen acceptor and oxidant in organic synthesis.
[src:aniline/1-4-benzoquinone] 1,4-Benzoquinone serves as a dehydrogenation reagent.
[src:aniline/1-4-benzoquinone] It is also used as a dienophile in Diels-Alder reactions.
[src:aniline/1-4-benzoquinone] Benzoquinone reacts with acetic anhydride and sulfuric acid to give the triacetate of hydroxyquinol.
[src:aniline/1-4-benzoquinone] This reaction is called the **Thiele reaction** or **Thiele–Winter reaction** after Johannes Thiele, who first described it in 1898, and after Ernst Winter, who further described its reaction mechanism in 1900.
[src:aniline/1-4-benzoquinone] Benzoquinone is also used to suppress double-bond migration during olefin metathesis reactions.
[src:aniline/1-4-benzoquinone] An acidic potassium iodide solution reduces a solution of benzoquinone to hydroquinone, which can be reoxidized back to the quinone with a solution of silver nitrate.
[src:aniline/1-4-benzoquinone] Due to its ability to function as an oxidizer, 1,4-benzoquinone can be found in methods using the Wacker-Tsuji oxidation, wherein a palladium salt catalyzes the conversion of an alkene to a ketone.
[src:aniline/1-4-benzoquinone] This reaction is typically carried out using pressurized oxygen as the oxidizer, but benzoquinone can sometimes preferred.
[src:aniline/1-4-benzoquinone] It is also used as a reagent in some variants on Wacker oxidations.
[src:aniline/1-4-benzoquinone] 1,4-Benzoquinone is used in the synthesis of Bromadol and related analogs.
[src:aniline/1-4-benzoquinone] 2,3-Dichloro-5,6-dicyano-1,4-benzoquinone (DDQ) is a stronger oxidant and dehydrogenation agent than 1,4-benzoquinone.
[src:aniline/1-4-benzoquinone] Chloranil 1,4-C6Cl4O2 is another potent oxidant and dehydrogenation agent.
[src:aniline/1-4-benzoquinone] Monochloro-p-benzoquinone is yet another but milder oxidant.
[src:aniline/1-4-benzoquinone] 1,4-Benzoquinone is a toxic metabolite found in human blood and can be used to track exposure to benzene or mixtures containing benzene and benzene compounds, such as petrol.
[src:aniline/1-4-benzoquinone] The compound can interfere with cellular respiration, and kidney damage has been found in animals receiving severe exposure.
[src:aniline/1-4-benzoquinone] It is excreted in its original form and also as variations of its own metabolite, hydroquinone.
[src:aniline/1-4-benzoquinone] 1,4-Benzoquinone is able to stain skin dark brown, cause erythema (redness, rashes on skin) and lead on to localized tissue necrosis.
[src:aniline/1-4-benzoquinone] It is particularly irritating to the eyes and respiratory system.
[src:aniline/1-4-benzoquinone] Its ability to sublime at commonly encountered temperatures allows for a greater airborne exposure risk than might be expected for a room-temperature solid.
[src:aniline/1-4-benzoquinone] IARC has found insufficient evidence to comment on the compound's carcinogenicity, but has noted that it can easily pass into the bloodstream and that it showed activity in depressing bone marrow production in mice and can inhibit protease enzymes involved in cellular apoptosis.
[src:aniline/1-naphthylamine] It can be prepared by reducing 1-nitronaphthalene with iron and hydrochloric acid followed by steam distillation.
[src:aniline/1-naphthylamine] Oxidizing agents, such as ferric chloride, give a blue precipitate with solutions of its salts.
[src:aniline/1-naphthylamine] Chromic acid converts it into 1,4-naphthoquinone.
[src:aniline/1-naphthylamine] Sodium in boiling amyl alcohol reduces the unsubstituted ring, giving tetrahydro-1-naphthylamine.
[src:aniline/1-naphthylamine] This tetrahydro compound yields adipic acid when oxidized by potassium permanganate.
[src:aniline/1-naphthylamine] At 200 °C in sulfuric acid, it converts to 1-naphthol.
[src:aniline/1-naphthylamine] The sulfonic acid derivatives of 1-naphthylamine are used for the preparation of azo dye.
[src:aniline/1-naphthylamine] These compounds possess the important property of dyeing unmordanted cotton.
[src:aniline/1-naphthylamine] An important derivative is naphthionic acid (1-aminonaphthalene-4-sulfonic acid), which is produced by heating 1-naphthylamine and sulfuric acid to 170–180 °C in the presence of crystallized oxalic acid.
[src:aniline/1-naphthylamine] It forms small needles, very sparingly soluble in water.
[src:aniline/1-naphthylamine] Upon treatment with the bis(diazonium) derivative of benzidine, 1-aminonaphthalene-4-sulfonic acid gives Congo red.
[src:aniline/1-naphthylamine] It is listed as one of the 13 carcinogens covered by the OSHA General Industry Standards.
[src:aniline/2-4-6-tribromoaniline] Diazotization, then reaction with ethanol to replace the diazonium group with hydrogen, gives 1,3,5-tribromobenzene.
[src:aniline/2-4-6-trinitroaniline] Trinitroaniline is only used in modern times in the small warheads of some explosive devices such as mortars.
[src:aniline/2-4-6-trinitroaniline] In World War II it was used by Imperial Japanese Navy as **Type 97 *bakuyaku*** (Model 1931 explosive) in some versions of gun projectiles instead of less stable burster *schimose* (picric acid).
[src:aniline/2-4-6-trinitroaniline] It was also used in the Yokosuka MXY-7 Ohka, a kamikaze antishipping human-guided rocket aircraft.
[src:aniline/2-4-6-trinitroaniline] Trinitroaniline is dangerously explosive and also hepatoxic.
[src:aniline/2-4-6-trinitroaniline] Symptoms of exposure to this compound may include skin and eye irritation, headache, drowsiness, weakness, cyanosis, and respiratory distress.
[src:aniline/2-naphthylamine] 2-Naphthylamine is prepared by heating 2-naphthol with ammonium zinc chloride to 200-210 °C, the Bucherer reaction.
[src:aniline/2-naphthylamine] Its acetyl derivative can be obtained by heating 2-naphthol with ammonium acetate to 270-280 °C.
[src:aniline/2-naphthylamine] It gives no color with iron(III) chloride.
[src:aniline/2-naphthylamine] When reduced by sodium in boiling amyl alcohol solution, it forms tetrahydro-3-naphthylamine, which exhibits the properties of the aliphatic amines in that it is strongly alkaline in reaction, has an ammoniacal odor and cannot be diazotized.
[src:aniline/2-naphthylamine] On oxidation, it yields *ortho*-carboxy-hydrocinnamic acid, HO2CC6H4CH2CH2CO2H.
[src:aniline/2-naphthylamine] Numerous sulfonic acid derivatives of 2-naphthylamine are used in commerce, such as precursors to dyes.
[src:aniline/2-naphthylamine] Owing to the carcinogenicity of the amine, these derivatives are mainly prepared by amination of the corresponding naphthols.
[src:aniline/2-naphthylamine] Of them, the δ-acid and Bronner's acid are of more value technically, since they combine with *ortho*-tetrazoditolyl to produce fine red dye-stuffs.
[src:aniline/2-naphthylamine] 2-Naphthylamine was previously used as a dye precursor and rubber antioxidant in the 1930s, 40s and 50s.
[src:aniline/2-naphthylamine] 2-Naphthylamine is found in cigarette smoke and suspected to contribute to the development of bladder cancer.
[src:aniline/2-naphthylamine] It is activated in the liver but quickly deactivated by conjugation to glucuronic acid.
[src:aniline/2-naphthylamine] In the bladder, glucuronidase re-activates it by deconjugation, which leads to the development of bladder cancer.
[src:aniline/3-methylaniline] There are three isomers of **toluidine**, which are organic compounds discovered and named by James Sheridan Muspratt and August Wilhelm von Hofmann in 1845.
[src:aniline/3-methylaniline] These isomers are ***o*-toluidine**, ***m*-toluidine**, and ***p*-toluidine**, with the prefixed letter abbreviating, respectively, *ortho*; *meta*; and *para*.
[src:aniline/3-methylaniline] All three are aryl amines whose chemical structures are similar to aniline except that a methyl group is substituted onto the benzene ring.
[src:aniline/3-methylaniline] The difference between these three isomers is the position where the methyl group (–CH3) is bonded to the ring relative to the amino functional group (–NH2); see illustration of the chemical structures below.
[src:aniline/3-methylaniline] The chemical properties of the toluidines are quite similar to those of aniline, and toluidines have properties in common with other aromatic amines.
[src:aniline/3-methylaniline] Due to the amino group bonded to the aromatic ring, the toluidines are weakly basic.
[src:aniline/3-methylaniline] The toluidines are poorly soluble in pure water but dissolve well in acidic water due to formation of ammonium salts, as usual for organic amines.
[src:aniline/3-methylaniline] *ortho*- and *meta*-toluidines are viscous liquids, but *para*-toluidine is a flaky solid.
[src:aniline/3-methylaniline] This difference is related to the fact that the *p*-toluidine molecules are more symmetrical.
[src:aniline/3-methylaniline] *p*-Toluidine can be obtained from reduction of *p*-nitrotoluene.
[src:aniline/3-methylaniline] *p*-Toluidine reacts with formaldehyde to form Tröger's base.
[src:aniline/3-methylaniline] The *ortho* isomer is produced on the largest scale.
[src:aniline/3-methylaniline] Its primary application is as a precursor to the pesticides metolachlor and acetochlor.
[src:aniline/3-methylaniline] The other toluidine isomers are used in the production of dyes such as Allura Red AC (Red 40, E129) and azorubine (carmoisine, E122).
[src:aniline/3-methylaniline] They are a component of accelerators for cyanoacrylate glues.
[src:aniline/3-methylaniline] In some patients *o*-toluidine is a metabolite of prilocaine, which may cause methemoglobinemia.
[src:aniline/3-methylaniline] This is then treated with methylene blue.
[src:aniline/aniline] Relative to benzene, aniline is "electron-rich".
[src:aniline/aniline] It thus participates more rapidly in electrophilic aromatic substitution reactions.
[src:aniline/aniline] Likewise, it is also prone to oxidation: while freshly purified aniline is an almost colorless oil, exposure to air results in gradual darkening to yellow or red, due to the formation of strongly colored, oxidized impurities.
[src:aniline/aniline] Aniline can be diazotized to give a diazonium salt, which can then undergo various nucleophilic substitution reactions.
[src:aniline/aniline] Like other amines, aniline is both a base (p*K*aH = 4.6) and a nucleophile, although less so than structurally similar aliphatic amines.
[src:aniline/aniline] Because an early source of the benzene from which they are derived was coal tar, aniline dyes are also called **coal tar dyes**.
[src:aniline/aniline] In aniline, the C−N bond length is 1.41 Å, compared to the C−N bond length of 1.47 Å for cyclohexylamine, indicating partial π-bonding between C(aryl) and N.
[src:aniline/aniline] The length of the chemical bond of C(aryl)−NH2 in anilines is highly sensitive to substituent effects.
[src:aniline/aniline] The C−N bond length is 1.34 Å in 2,4,6-trinitroaniline vs 1.44 Å in 3-methylaniline.
[src:aniline/aniline] The amine group in anilines is slightly pyramidal.
[src:aniline/aniline] The hybridization of nitrogen is describe somewhere between sp3 and sp2.
[src:aniline/aniline] The lone pair of electrons on nitrogen have high p character.
[src:aniline/aniline] The amino group in aniline is flatter (i.e., it is a "shallower pyramid") than that in an aliphatic amine, an effect attributed to conjugation of the lone pair with the aryl substituent.
[src:aniline/aniline] Consistent with these factors, substituted anilines with electron donating groups are more pyramidalized, while those with electron withdrawing groups are more planar.
[src:aniline/aniline] In the parent aniline, the lone pair is approximately 12% s character, corresponding to sp7.3 hybridization.
[src:aniline/aniline] The pyramidalization angle between the C–N bond and the bisector of the H–N–H angle is 142.5°.
[src:aniline/aniline] For comparison, in more strongly pyramidal amine group in methylamine, this value is ~125°, while that of the amine group in formamide has an angle of 180°.
[src:aniline/aniline] Industrial aniline production involves hydrogenation of nitrobenzene (typically at 200–300 °C) in the presence of metal catalysts: Approximately 4 million tonnes are produced annually.
[src:aniline/aniline] Catalysts include nickel, copper, palladium, and platinum, and newer catalysts continue to be discovered.
[src:aniline/aniline] The reduction of nitrobenzene to aniline was first performed by Nikolay Zinin in 1842, using sulfide salts (Zinin reaction).
[src:aniline/aniline] The reduction of nitrobenzene to aniline was also performed as part of reductions by Antoine Béchamp in 1854, using iron as the reductant (Bechamp reduction).
[src:aniline/aniline] These stoichiometric routes remain useful for specialty anilines.
[src:aniline/aniline] Aniline can alternatively be prepared from ammonia and phenol derived from the cumene process.
[src:aniline/aniline] Many analogues and derivatives of aniline are known where the phenyl group is further substituted.
[src:aniline/aniline] These include toluidines, xylidines, chloroanilines, aminobenzoic acids, nitroanilines, and many others.
[src:aniline/aniline] They also are usually prepared by nitration of the substituted aromatic compounds followed by reduction.
[src:aniline/aniline] For example, this approach is used to convert toluene into toluidines and chlorobenzene into 4-chloroaniline.
[src:aniline/aniline] Alternatively, using Buchwald-Hartwig coupling or Ullmann reaction approaches, aryl halides can be aminated with aqueous or gaseous ammonia.
[src:aniline/aniline] The chemistry of aniline is rich because the compound has been cheaply available for many years.
[src:aniline/aniline] Below are some classes of its reactions.
[src:aniline/aniline] The oxidation of aniline has been heavily investigated, and can result in reactions localized at nitrogen or more commonly results in the formation of new C-N bonds.
[src:aniline/aniline] In alkaline solution, azobenzene results, whereas arsenic acid produces the violet-coloring matter violaniline.
[src:aniline/aniline] Chromic acid converts it into quinone, whereas chlorates, in the presence of certain metallic salts (especially of vanadium), give aniline black.
[src:aniline/aniline] Hydrochloric acid and potassium chlorate give chloranil.
[src:aniline/aniline] Potassium permanganate in neutral solution oxidizes it to nitrobenzene; in alkaline solution to azobenzene, ammonia, and oxalic acid; in acid solution to aniline black.
[src:aniline/aniline] Hypochlorous acid gives 4-aminophenol and para-amino diphenylamine.
[src:aniline/aniline] Oxidation with persulfate affords a variety of polyanilines.
[src:aniline/aniline] These polymers exhibit rich redox and acid-base properties.
[src:aniline/aniline] Like phenols, aniline derivatives are highly susceptible to electrophilic substitution reactions.
[src:aniline/aniline] Its high reactivity reflects that it is an enamine, which enhances the electron-donating ability of the ring.
[src:aniline/aniline] For example, reaction of aniline with sulfuric acid at 180 °C produces sulfanilic acid, H2NC6H4SO3H.
[src:aniline/aniline] If bromine water is added to aniline, the bromine water is decolourised and a white precipitate of 2,4,6-tribromoaniline is formed.
[src:aniline/aniline] The reaction to form 4-bromoaniline is to protect the amine with acetyl chloride, then hydrolyse back to reform aniline.
[src:aniline/aniline] The largest scale industrial reaction of aniline involves its alkylation with formaldehyde.
[src:aniline/aniline] The resulting diamine is the precursor to 4,4'-MDI and related diisocyanates.
[src:aniline/aniline] Aromatic amines such as aniline are, in general, much weaker bases than aliphatic amines.
[src:aniline/aniline] Aniline reacts with strong acids to form the anilinium (or phenylammonium) ion (C6H5−NH+3).
[src:aniline/aniline] Traditionally, the weak basicity of aniline is attributed to a combination of inductive effect from the more electronegative sp2 carbon and resonance effects, as the lone pair on the nitrogen is partially delocalized into the pi system of the benzene ring.
[src:aniline/aniline] Missing in such an analysis is consideration of solvation.
[src:aniline/aniline] Aniline is, for example, more basic than ammonia in the gas phase, but ten thousand times less so in aqueous solution.
[src:aniline/aniline] Aniline reacts with acyl chlorides such as acetyl chloride to give amides.
[src:aniline/aniline] The amides formed from aniline are sometimes called anilides, for example CH3−C(=O)−NH−C6H5 is acetanilide.
[src:aniline/aniline] At high temperatures aniline and carboxylic acids react to give the anilides.
[src:aniline/aniline] Boiled with carbon disulfide, it gives sulfocarbanilide (diphenylthiourea) (S=C(−NH−C6H5)2), which may be decomposed into phenyl isothiocyanate (C6H5−N=C=S), and triphenyl guanidine (C6H5−N=C(−NH−C6H5)2).
[src:aniline/aniline] Aniline and its ring-substituted derivatives react with nitrous acid to form diazonium salts.
[src:aniline/aniline] One example is benzenediazonium tetrafluoroborate.
[src:aniline/aniline] Through these intermediates, the amine group can be converted to a hydroxyl (−OH), cyanide (−CN), or halide group (−X, where X is a halogen) via Sandmeyer reactions.
[src:aniline/aniline] This diazonium salt can also be reacted with NaNO2 and phenol to produce a dye known as benzeneazophenol, in a process called *coupling*.
[src:aniline/aniline] The reaction of converting primary aromatic amine into diazonium salt is called diazotisation.
[src:aniline/aniline] In this reaction primary aromatic amine is allowed to react with sodium nitrite and 2 moles of HCl, which is known as "ice cold mixture" because the temperature for the reaction was as low as 0.5 °C.
[src:aniline/aniline] The benzene diazonium salt is formed as major product alongside the byproducts water and sodium chloride.
[src:aniline/aniline] It reacts with nitrobenzene to produce phenazine in the Wohl–Aue reaction.
[src:aniline/aniline] Being a standard reagent in laboratories, aniline is used for many niche reactions.
[src:aniline/aniline] Its acetate is used in the aniline acetate test for carbohydrates, identifying pentoses by conversion to furfural.
[src:aniline/aniline] It is used to stain neural RNA blue in the Nissl stain.
[src:aniline/aniline] In addition, aniline is the starting component in the production of diglycidyl aniline.
[src:aniline/aniline] Epichlorohydrin is the other main ingredient.
[src:aniline/aniline] Aniline is predominantly used for the preparation of methylenedianiline and related compounds by condensation with formaldehyde.
[src:aniline/aniline] The diamines are condensed with phosgene to give methylene diphenyl diisocyanate, a precursor to urethane polymers.
[src:aniline/aniline] Other uses include rubber processing chemicals (9%), herbicides (2%), and dyes and pigments (2%).
[src:aniline/aniline] As additives to rubber, aniline derivatives such as phenylenediamines and diphenylamine, are antioxidants.
[src:aniline/aniline] Illustrative of the drugs prepared from aniline is paracetamol (acetaminophen, Tylenol).
[src:aniline/aniline] The principal use of aniline in the dye industry is as a precursor to indigo, the blue of blue jeans.
[src:aniline/aniline] Aniline oil is also used for mushroom identification.
[src:aniline/aniline] Kerrigan's 2016 Agaricus of North America P45: (Referring to Schaffer's reaction) "In fact I recommend switching to the following modified test.
[src:aniline/aniline] Frank (1988) developed an alternative formulation in which aniline oil is combined with glacial acetic acid (GAA, essentially distilled vinegar) in a 50:50 solution.
[src:aniline/aniline] GAA is a much safer, less reactive acid.
[src:aniline/aniline] This single combined reagent is relatively stable over time.
[src:aniline/aniline] A single spot or line applied to the pileus (or other surface).
[src:aniline/aniline] Aniline was first isolated in 1826 by Otto Unverdorben by destructive distillation of indigo.
[src:aniline/aniline] In 1834, Friedlieb Runge isolated a substance from coal tar that turned a beautiful blue color when treated with chloride of lime.
[src:aniline/aniline] In 1840, Carl Julius Fritzsche (1808–1871) treated indigo with caustic potash and obtained an oil that he named *aniline*, after an indigo-yielding plant, anil (*Indigofera suffruticosa*).
[src:aniline/aniline] In 1842, Nikolay Nikolaevich Zinin reduced nitrobenzene and obtained a base that he named *benzidam*.
[src:aniline/aniline] In 1843, August Wilhelm von Hofmann showed that these were all the same substance, known thereafter as *phenylamine* or *aniline*.
[src:aniline/aniline] In 1856, while trying to synthesise quinine, von Hofmann's student William Henry Perkin discovered mauveine.
[src:aniline/aniline] Mauveine quickly became a commercial dye.
[src:aniline/aniline] Other synthetic dyes followed, such as fuchsin, safranin, and induline.
[src:aniline/aniline] At the time of mauveine's discovery, aniline was expensive.
[src:aniline/aniline] Soon thereafter, applying a method reported in 1854 by Antoine Béchamp, it was prepared "by the ton".
[src:aniline/aniline] The Béchamp reduction enabled the evolution of a massive dye industry in Germany.
[src:aniline/aniline] Today, the name of BASF, originally *Badische Anilin- und Soda-Fabrik* (English: Baden Aniline and Soda Factory), now the largest chemical supplier, echoes the legacy of the synthetic dye industry, built via aniline dyes and extended via the related azo dyes.
[src:aniline/aniline] In the late 19th century, derivatives of aniline such as acetanilide and phenacetin emerged as analgesic drugs, with their cardiac-suppressive side effects often countered with caffeine.
[src:aniline/aniline] Also in the late 19th century, Ehrlich found that the aniline dye methylene blue works as an antimalarial drug.
[src:aniline/aniline] He hypothesized that dyes that selectively stain pathogens over tissue would prefentially harm pathogens, leading to his "magic bullet" concept.
[src:aniline/aniline] Salvarsan's targeted microorganism, not yet recognized as a bacterium, was still thought to be a parasite, and medical bacteriologists, believing that bacteria were not susceptible to the chemotherapeutic approach, overlooked Alexander Fleming's report in 1928 on the effects of penicillin.
[src:aniline/aniline] In 1932, Bayer sought medical applications of its dyes.
[src:aniline/aniline] By the 1940s, over 500 related sulfa drugs were produced.
[src:aniline/aniline] Medications in high demand during World War II (1939–45), these first *miracle drugs*, chemotherapy of wide effectiveness, propelled the American pharmaceutics industry.
[src:aniline/aniline] In 1939, at Oxford University, seeking an alternative to sulfa drugs, Howard Florey developed Fleming's penicillin into the first systemic antibiotic drug, penicillin G.
[src:aniline/aniline] (Gramicidin, developed by René Dubos at Rockefeller Institute in 1939, was the first antibiotic, yet its toxicity restricted it to topical use.) After World War II, Cornelius P.
[src:aniline/aniline] Rhoads introduced the chemotherapeutic approach to cancer treatment.
[src:aniline/aniline] Some early American rockets, such as the Aerobee and WAC Corporal, used a mixture of aniline and furfuryl alcohol as a fuel, with nitric acid as an oxidizer.
[src:aniline/aniline] The combination is hypergolic, igniting on contact between fuel and oxidizer.
[src:aniline/aniline] It is also dense, and can be stored for extended periods.
[src:aniline/aniline] Aniline was later replaced by hydrazine.
[src:aniline/aniline] Aniline is toxic by inhalation of the vapour, ingestion, or percutaneous absorption.
[src:aniline/aniline] The IARC lists it in Group 2A (*Probably carcinogenic to humans*), and it has specifically been linked to bladder cancer.
[src:aniline/aniline] Aniline has been implicated as one possible cause of forest dieback.
[src:aniline/aniline] Many methods exist for the detection of aniline.
[src:aniline/aniline] Exposure of rats to aniline can elicit a response that is toxic to the spleen, including a tumorigenic response.
[src:aniline/aniline] Rats exposed to aniline in drinking water, showed a significant increase in oxidative DNA damage to the spleen, detected as a 2.8-fold increase in 8-hydroxy-2'-deoxyguanosine (8-OHdG) in their DNA.
[src:aniline/aniline] Although the base excision repair pathway was also activated, its activity was not sufficient to prevent the accumulation of 8-OHdG.
[src:aniline/aniline] The accumulation of oxidative DNA damages in the spleen following exposure to aniline may increase mutagenic events that underlie tumorigenesis.
